Plotter!

A scientific plotting program by Bill Destler

This program may be freely distributed but not sold.

What you need to know:

     Plotter! is a scientific plotting package written in GFA 
Basic.  Although it can be compiled, it is best run out of the 
GFA interpreter since functions can be easily redefined from 
within the editor.  The program is designed to:

     1. Plot any function y=f(x) over any specified range of x
        (the y coordinate scaling is done automatically)

     2. Plot points in the x-y plane.  Up to 2 sets of points 
        can be plotted with up to 500 points in each set.

     3. Both types of plotting can be done with 100 different 
        point sizes and plotted points can be connected with one
        of six different line types.

     4. Plots may be titled, and names may be given to the x and 
        y axes.

     5. Plots may be saved to and loaded from disk and may be 
        printed on any printer for which there is a desktop
        printer driver.

     6. Plots may include grids if desired.

     7. Negative values of either functions or individual points
        are handled automatically.

     Operation of the program is self explanatory once you have 
read the above notes.  The function contained in the original 
program is y = sin(x).  This may be easily changed as the 
function is defined in the first line of the program.  The file
CPLOTTER.BAS is the color version and the file MPLOTTER.BAS is 
the monochrome version.  

Comments and improvements are welcome.
